>>>>> On 22 Sep 92 01:05:39 GMT, capsalad@uful07.phys.ufl.edu (Dave Schulman) said:



Dave> BTW, I was kind of irritated by _Sneakers_, even if Len Adelman was
Dave> (too briefly) consulted by the filmmakers.  Didn't he tell them what
Dave> it would mean if somebody found a super-algorithm to solve a
Dave> (supposedly) NP-complete problem in polynomial time?  Since all the
Dave> NP-complete problems can be reduced to the same problem, any algorithm
Dave> that solved one could thus be modified to solve them all, and there
Dave> would be no such thing as NP-completeness any more... this would be a
Dave> TREMENDOUS discovery, and cryptography would be the least of its many
Dave> ramifications... also, as Oppenheimer said, you can't put the djinn
Dave> back in the bottle; a scientific discovery, once made, can be made
Dave> again!

Dave> For this reason I haven't got much patience for the many, many book &
Dave> movie plots in which some evil organization tries to restrict the flow
Dave> of knowledge in some way by killing the brilliant scientist (who, of
Dave> course, told nobody of his work -- yeah right), or stealing/destroying
Dave> the SECRET FORMULA for whatever, or... well, you know the type.  It's
Dave> annoying, but, like someone on this newsgroup said earlier, there are
Dave> certain sacrifices that must be made for the sake of mass-market
Dave> entertainment... at least in some scientifically backward societies...
Dave> :-(.

Dave, It was pretty clear (at least to me) that what Janek had done
was to find a fast factoring algorithm.  His lecture was about the
Number Field Sieve, and contained some of the standard current
speculation about possible ways of speeding it up.

Dave> Information is neither good nor evil!  It just is.


